Sorry to hear about this ADHD thing. Now I see you did not over exaggerate when you wrote about your boy driving you mad (I thought you were kiddin a bit like all parents do now and then). I don't know much about it. I've read a few things in the past (you know you get all these magazines from the manufacturers of baby products as soon as you have kids) and I remember a really touching story of a mother who was left alone with her boy, because her husband couldn't stand it. Also when friends invited her, she was asked to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bring her kid with her<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  He must have been the kind of tornado you are talking about. Anyways, at about the age of 12 she found out (I don't remember the circumstances, but a lot of luck was involved) that in his case the absence of phosphates in his nutrition would simply make him a normal boy. I think it was mainly food based on milk and things like sausages that come with factory added phosphate, which she took out of his daily meals. &quot;I got a completely new kid&quot; she said &quot;We both lead a happy life now.&quot;. Maybe there's something like this for everybody suffering from ADHD.<br>
<br>
Andrew, glad to hear you found a way to handle it. And don't worry about the topic, nor about getting pointless. I do it all the time and no one complained yet and there are even people left that talk to me<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Interesting that you were about 12 years old too. Was it possible that it actually helps when your hormone factory kicks in?<br>
